<strong>Unit: </strong>Chemistry of Carbon

<em>Lesson 3</em>

<em>Textbook</em> (AP Campbell Biology, Tenth Edition; Chapter 5, p. 66)

<hr />

<h1><span style="font-weight:400;">Proteins</span></h1>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Proteins make up more than 50% of dry mass of most cells</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Carry oxygen (hemoglobin); form antibodies to fight diseases; form muscles</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Made up of C, H, O, and N</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Proteins can also contain Sulphur, Phosphorus, and Iron</span></li>
</ul>
<img class="size-full wp-image-152 aligncenter" src="https://apbiology387631959.files.wordpress.com/2018/01/screen-shot-2018-01-04-at-1-56-09-pm.png" alt="Screen Shot 2018-01-04 at 1.56.09 PM.png" width="258" height="310" />
<h1><span style="font-weight:400;">Polypeptides</span></h1>
<ul>
	<li style="list-style-type:none;">
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">2 amino acids combine by dehydration synthesis to form a dipeptide</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">They are linked together by a </span><span style="font-weight:400;">peptide bond</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<ul>
	<li><b>Polypeptide:<span style="font-weight:400;"> long chain of amino acids</span></b></li>
	<li>Different polypeptides may link to form a protein molecule</li>
</ul>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Structure</span></h2>
<ol>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Primary structure = amino acid sequence (determined by the sequence of ACTG in the gene)</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Secondary structure = coiled to form α-helix or ß-pleated sheets, which are held together by hydrogen bonding</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Tertiary shape = folded into a specific shape by disulfide bonds (R-group interaction)</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">At this point the protein is functional</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">However, some tertiary structures combine into one large molecule in order to fulfill their purpose</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Quaternary structure = the joining of orienting more than one polypeptide chain to form a functional molecule: </span><span style="font-weight:400;">not all molecules do that</span></li>
</ol>
<h1><span style="font-weight:400;">Protein Groups</span></h1>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Fibrous</span></h3>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Long parallel chains forming fibers or sheets</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">ex. Connective tissue, tendons, bone matrix, and muscle fibers</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Globular</span></h3>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Have tertiary structure, easily soluble, </span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">ex. enzymes, plasma proteins, and hormones</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h3><span style="font-weight:400;">Conjugated</span></h3>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Have prosthetic (non-protein) groups</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">ex. Haemoglobin has Iron</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<img class="size-full wp-image-153 aligncenter" src="https://apbiology387631959.files.wordpress.com/2018/01/screen-shot-2018-01-04-at-1-56-58-pm.png" alt="Screen Shot 2018-01-04 at 1.56.58 PM.png" width="485" height="370" />
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Other Information</span></h2>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Form is related to function</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Globular and fibrous proteins are held together by hydrogen bonds</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Under high temperature and/or change in pH, they break down and the polypeptide chains unfold.</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The protein is denatured and is irreparably dysfunctional </span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">This is why having a high fever is dangerous, as the high temperatures within the body can denature cells</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h2><span style="font-weight:400;">Protein Functions</span></h2>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Building material</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Collagen in cartilage, bones, tendons, and blood vessel walls</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Protection against disease</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Antibodies</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Transport</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Hemoglobin</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Movement</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Contractile proteins in muscle</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Catalyzing metabolic reactions</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Enzymes are biological catalysts</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Coordination of body activities</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Neurotransmitters and hormones</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Storage of amino acids</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Proteins can be broken down to release amino acids to make new proteins</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h1><span style="font-weight:400;">Protein Structure</span></h1>
<ul>
	<li style="list-style-type:none;">
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Macromolecules made up of monomers</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Monomers of proteins are amino acids</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">There are 20 important amino acids that combine to make thousands of proteins</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><i><span style="font-weight:400;">All amino acids have the same general formula</span></i></li>
	<li style="list-style-type:none;">
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Amino acids have an </span><b>amine group</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> NH</span><span style="font-weight:400;">2</span><span style="font-weight:400;">- at one ends of the molecule and a </span><b>carboxyl group</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> -COOH at the other end </span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The </span><b>R</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> group consists of different atoms in different amino acids</span></li>
	<li><b>A protein’s specific shape determines its function</b></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">In almost every case, the function depends on its ability to recognize and bind to some other molecules</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">ex. (1) Antibodies bind to particular foreign substances that fit their binding sites, enzymes recognize and bind to specific substrates, (2) facilitating a chemical reaction, (3) neurotransmitters pass signals from one cell to another by binding o receptor sites on proteins in the membranes of the receiving cell</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<h2><b>Primary structure</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> of a protein is its unique sequence of amino acids</span></h2>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The bonds between each amino acid are called peptide bonds</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Lysozyme, an enzyme that attacks bacteria consists of a polypeptide chain of 129 amino acids</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Even a slight change in primary structure can affect a protein's conformation and ability to function</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Even just changing one amino acid can change the makeup of the protein</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">ex. In individuals with sickle cell disease, abnormal hemoglobins, oxygen-carrying proteins, develop because of a single amino acid substitution. These abnormal hemoglobins crystallize, deforming the red blood cells and leading to clogs in tiny blood vessels</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<img class="aligncenter size-full wp-image-154" src="https://apbiology387631959.files.wordpress.com/2018/01/screen-shot-2018-01-04-at-1-58-15-pm.png" alt="Screen Shot 2018-01-04 at 1.58.15 PM.png" width="315" height="517" />
<h2><b>Secondary structure</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> of a protein results from hydrogen bonds along the polypeptide backbone</span></h2>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The polypeptide is created by the sequence of amino acids</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Typical shapes that develop from a secondary structure are </span><b>coils (α helix) </b><span style="font-weight:400;">or </span><b>folds (ß pleated sheets)</b></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">ex. The structural properties of silk are due to ß-pleated sheets. The presence of so many hydrogen bonds make each silk fiber stronger than steel</span></li>
</ul>
<img class="size-full wp-image-155 aligncenter" src="https://apbiology387631959.files.wordpress.com/2018/01/screen-shot-2018-01-04-at-1-58-26-pm.png" alt="Screen Shot 2018-01-04 at 1.58.26 PM.png" width="418" height="425" />
<h2><b>Tertiary structure</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> of a protein is determined by a variety of interactions among R groups and between R groups and the polypeptide backbone</span></h2>
<span style="font-weight:400;">R-group interactions</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Ionic bonding</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Hydrogen bonding</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Covalent disulfide bridges</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Hydrophobic interactions</span></li>
</ul>
<img class="size-full wp-image-156 aligncenter" src="https://apbiology387631959.files.wordpress.com/2018/01/screen-shot-2018-01-04-at-1-58-34-pm.png" alt="Screen Shot 2018-01-04 at 1.58.34 PM.png" width="552" height="454" />
<h2><b>Quaternary structure</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> results from the aggregation of two or more polypeptide subunits</span></h2>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">ex. Collagen is a fibrous protein of three polypeptides that are supercoiled like a rope. </span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Provides the structural strength for their role in connective tissue</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">ex. Hemoglobin is a globular protein with two copies of polypeptides</span></li>
</ul>
<img class="size-full wp-image-157 aligncenter" src="https://apbiology387631959.files.wordpress.com/2018/01/screen-shot-2018-01-04-at-1-58-41-pm.png" alt="Screen Shot 2018-01-04 at 1.58.41 PM.png" width="445" height="366" /><img class="size-full wp-image-158 aligncenter" src="https://apbiology387631959.files.wordpress.com/2018/01/screen-shot-2018-01-04-at-1-58-46-pm.png" alt="Screen Shot 2018-01-04 at 1.58.46 PM.png" width="579" height="274" />
<h1><span style="font-weight:400;">Nucleic Acids</span></h1>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">There are two types of nucleic acid: </span><b>ribonucleic acid (RNA)</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> and </span><b>deoxyribonucleic acid (DNA)</b></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Nucleic acids are polymers of monomers of polymers called </span><b>nucleotides</b></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Each nucleotide consists of three parts:</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">(1) nitrogen-containing base</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">(2) pentose sugar</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">(3) phosphate group</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-159" src="https://apbiology387631959.files.wordpress.com/2018/01/screen-shot-2018-01-04-at-1-58-54-pm.png" alt="Screen Shot 2018-01-04 at 1.58.54 PM.png" width="616" height="360" />

<span style="font-weight:400;">Why A & T and C & G Pair Together</span>
<ol>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The hydrogen bonds between the two amino acids can only pair with each other, as one pair has two hydrogen bonds and the other has three; they cannot bond with each other</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Pyrimidines and purines are always paired with each other so that the molecules are equidistant from each other - there is a large molecule paired with a small molecule</span>
<ol>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">C is  pyrimidine, and G is a purine</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">T is a pyrimidine and A is a purine</span></li>
</ol>
</li>
</ol>
<h1><span style="font-weight:400;">Structure</span></h1>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Nitrogen bases, rings of carbon and nitrogen, have two forms: </span><b>purines and pyrimidines</b>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Pyrimidines had a single six-membered ring</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The  three different pyrimidines cytosine (C), thymine (T), and uracil (U) are different in each ring</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Purines have a six-membered ring joined to a five-membered ring</span>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The two purines are adenine (A) and guanine (G)</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The pentose joined to the nitrogen base is </span><b>ribose</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> in nucleotides of </span><b>RNA</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> and </span><b>deoxyribose</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> in </span><b>DNA</b>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The only </span><b>difference</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> between the sugars is the </span><b>lack of an oxygen atom on carbon 2</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> in deoxyribose</span></li>
</ul>
</li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The addition of a phosphate group creates a nucleoside monophosphate or nucleotide</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Polynucleotides are synthesized by connection the sugars of one nucleotide to the phosphate of the next with a phosphodiester link</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">This creates a repeating backbone of sugar-phosphate units with the nitrogen bases as appendages</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">An RNA molecule is a single polypeptide chain</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">DNA molecules have 2 polynucleotide strands that spiral around an imaginary axis to form a double helix</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">The sugar-phosphate backbones of the two polynucleotides are on the outside of the helix</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Pairs of nitrogenous bases, one from each strand, connect the polynucleotide chains with hydrogen bonds</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">Most DNA molecules have thousands of millions of base pairs</span></li>
</ul>
<h1><span style="font-weight:400;">Function</span></h1>
<ul>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">DNA provides direction for its own replication</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">DNA also directs RNA synthesis and, through RNA, controls protein synthesis</span></li>
	<li style="font-weight:400;"><span style="font-weight:400;">It is an </span><b>informational polymer</b><span style="font-weight:400;"> - the genetic information that is needed to form the working organism</span></li>
</ul>
<img class="size-full wp-image-160 aligncenter" src="https://apbiology387631959.files.wordpress.com/2018/01/screen-shot-2018-01-04-at-1-59-02-pm.png" alt="Screen Shot 2018-01-04 at 1.59.02 PM.png" width="495" height="334" />
